Note: ================================================================
Note: HIR to LaTeX Backend
Note: ================================================================
Note: Generates LaTeX code from HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation).
Note: Produces idiomatic LaTeX for academic and scientific documents.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/latex/latex_to_hir.runa" as LaTeXHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

Note: ================================================================
Note: Backend State
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single owner of the emitter state for one LaTeX document. in_math_mode is a
flag rather than a counter because LaTeX math environments do not nest in a
way that requires depth tracking - inline $...$ inside display math is
syntactically rejected by LaTeX itself. in_preamble flips off at \begin{document}.
@End Reasoning
Type called "LaTeXBackend":
    output as String
    indent_level as Integer
    errors as Integer
    in_math_mode as Integer
    in_preamble as Integer
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Backend Creation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates 40 bytes (5 x 8-byte slots) to match the LaTeXBackend layout
exactly. The errors list is heap-allocated separately because lists carry
their own buffer that grows independently of the struct.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Offsets: 0=output string, 8=indent_level, 16=errors_list, 24=in_math_mode,
32=in_preamble. Defaults match the post-create_backend test fixture:
empty output, zero indent, empty errors list, no math mode, in preamble.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_backend" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Let backend_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 40

    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with backend_ptr, 0, ""
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 8, 0

    Let errors_list be proc list_create from ListCore
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 16, errors_list

    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 32, 0

    Return backend_ptr
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Main Translation Entry Point
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point dispatch: a top-level HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT routes through the
document-aware path that splits preamble from body; anything else lowers
through generate_hir_node so the backend can serve as a fragment generator.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, hir_module as Integer returns String:
    If hir_module is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with hir_module, 0

    If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENT:
        proc generate_document with backend_ptr, hir_module
    Otherwise:
        Note: Try to generate as generic HIR
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, hir_module
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with backend_ptr, 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Document Structure Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
LaTeX strictly separates preamble (\documentclass, \usepackage, metadata)
from body (after \begin{document}). We partition the HIR items in one pass
into two sub-lists, emit the preamble first, then \begin{document}, then
body, then \end{document} so the output is always well-formed.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Partition criterion: documentclass, usepackage, and metadata go to
preamble; everything else goes to body. The in_preamble flag toggles at
\begin{document} so child generators (e.g., escape_latex_text) can adapt.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_document" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, doc_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set preamble flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 32, 1

    Note: Get document items
    Let items_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with doc_ptr, 16

    If items_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Process all items, separating preamble and body
    Let preamble_items be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let body_items be proc list_create from ListCore

    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with items_list
    Let index be 0
    Let found_begin_document be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let item_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with items_list, index
        Let item_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 0

        Note: Preamble items
        If item_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS:
            proc list_append from ListCore with preamble_items, item_ptr
        Otherwise If item_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_USEPACKAGE:
            proc list_append from ListCore with preamble_items, item_ptr
        Otherwise If item_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
            proc list_append from ListCore with preamble_items, item_ptr
        Otherwise:
            Note: Body items
            proc list_append from ListCore with body_items, item_ptr
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Generate preamble
    proc generate_preamble with backend_ptr, preamble_items

    Note: Begin document
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\begin{document}\n"
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 32, 0

    Note: Generate body
    proc generate_item_list with backend_ptr, body_items

    Note: End document
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\end{document}\n"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preamble emitter dispatched per item type rather than per item index because
LaTeX preamble has no required ordering between documentclass/usepackage/
metadata commands (though documentclass must be first; that constraint is
enforced by the partitioning in generate_document).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_preamble" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, preamble_items as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with preamble_items
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let item_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with preamble_items, index
        Let item_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 0

        If item_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_DOCUMENTCLASS:
            proc generate_documentclass with backend_ptr, item_ptr
        Otherwise If item_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_USEPACKAGE:
            proc generate_usepackage with backend_ptr, item_ptr
        Otherwise If item_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
            proc generate_metadata_command with backend_ptr, item_ptr
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
\documentclass[options]{class} - options are bracketed (square brackets)
and must precede the class name in braces; the options string can be empty
so we test string length rather than null pointer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_documentclass" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, docclass_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\documentclass"

    Note: Add options if present
    Let options be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with docclass_ptr, 16
    If proc string_length from StringCore with options is greater than 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "["
        proc emit with backend_ptr, options
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "]"
    End If

    Note: Add class name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"
    Let class_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with docclass_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, class_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
\usepackage[options]{package} - same option syntax as documentclass. Mirrors
generate_documentclass deliberately so a future refactor can collapse them
behind a common "preamble bracket-brace command" emitter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_usepackage" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, package_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\usepackage"

    Note: Add options if present
    Let options be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with package_ptr, 16
    If proc string_length from StringCore with options is greater than 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "["
        proc emit with backend_ptr, options
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "]"
    End If

    Note: Add package name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"
    Let package_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with package_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, package_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preamble metadata commands like \title{...}, \author{...}, \date{...} share
a uniform shape: command name plus one or more brace-wrapped arguments.
Arguments may themselves be HIR nodes (e.g., \author{John \and Jane}) so we
recurse via generate_hir_node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_metadata_command" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, meta_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate preamble commands like \title, \author, \date
    Let command_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with meta_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, command_name

    Note: Generate arguments
    Let args_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with meta_ptr, 16
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with args_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let arg_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, index
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"
            proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, arg_ptr
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\n"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Item List Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Sequential generator for the document body; each item is dispatched through
generate_item which understands the full LaTeX-flavoured HIR node taxonomy.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_item_list" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, items_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with items_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let item_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with items_list, index
        proc generate_item with backend_ptr, item_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Large dispatch table covering every LaTeX-flavoured HIR node kind. Encoding
the per-kind logic as a flat If/Otherwise chain keeps the dispatch cost O(1)
in cache behaviour (single straight-line code path) versus the overhead of
a generic visitor table. Section types share a common emitter and differ
only by command name passed as the third argument.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_item" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, item_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If item_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 0

    Note: LaTeX-specific nodes
    If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_SECTION:
        Return proc generate_section with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "section"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_SUBSECTION:
        Return proc generate_section with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "subsection"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_SUBSUBSECTION:
        Return proc generate_section with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "subsubsection"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_PARAGRAPH:
        Return proc generate_section with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "paragraph"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_SUBPARAGRAPH:
        Return proc generate_section with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "subparagraph"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_ITEMIZE:
        Return proc generate_list_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "itemize"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_ENUMERATE:
        Return proc generate_list_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "enumerate"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_DESCRIPTION:
        Return proc generate_list_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "description"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_FIGURE:
        Return proc generate_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "figure"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_TABLE:
        Return proc generate_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "table"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_EQUATION:
        Return proc generate_equation_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_ENVIRONMENT:
        Return proc generate_generic_environment with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_TEXT_BOLD:
        Return proc generate_text_format with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "textbf"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_TEXT_ITALIC:
        Return proc generate_text_format with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "textit"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_TEXT_EMPH:
        Return proc generate_text_format with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "emph"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_TEXT_UNDERLINE:
        Return proc generate_text_format with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "underline"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_TEXT_TYPEWRITER:
        Return proc generate_text_format with backend_ptr, item_ptr, "texttt"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_INLINE:
        Return proc generate_math_inline with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_DISPLAY:
        Return proc generate_math_display with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_CITATION:
        Return proc generate_citation with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_REFERENCE:
        Return proc generate_reference with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_LABEL:
        Return proc generate_label with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_literal with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_block with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    Otherwise:
        Note: Generic HIR node
        Return proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, item_ptr
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Section Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
LaTeX section commands take an optional short title in brackets (used in
the table of contents and running headers when the full title is too long)
followed by the full title in braces. We emit a literal backslash because
LaTeX commands begin with \.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_section" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, section_ptr as Integer, section_type as String returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, section_type

    Note: Add short title if present
    Let short_title be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with section_ptr, 16
    If proc string_length from StringCore with short_title is greater than 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "["
        proc emit with backend_ptr, short_title
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "]"
    End If

    Note: Add main title
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"
    Let title be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with section_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, title
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Note: Generate section content
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with section_ptr, 24
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_content_list with backend_ptr, content_list
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Environment Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Generic LaTeX environment emitter: \begin{name}[params]...\end{name}.
Indentation increments inside the environment body so nested content reads
clearly in the generated source - LaTeX itself ignores indentation but
human readers and IDEs depend on it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_environment" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, env_ptr as Integer, env_name as String returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\begin{"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, env_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Note: Add parameters if present
    Let params be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with env_ptr, 16
    If proc string_length from StringCore with params is greater than 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "["
        proc emit with backend_ptr, params
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "]"
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\n"

    Note: Generate environment content
    proc indent_inc with backend_ptr
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 24
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_content_list with backend_ptr, content_list
    End If
    proc indent_dec with backend_ptr

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\end{"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, env_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Adapter for HIR_LATEX_ENVIRONMENT nodes whose name is stored as a runtime
string rather than baked into the node kind; reads the name and delegates
to the generic emitter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_generic_environment" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, env_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let env_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with env_ptr, 8
    Return proc generate_environment with backend_ptr, env_ptr, env_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
itemize/enumerate/description share a common shape: each child gets a
preceding \item, and description additionally takes an optional label in
brackets. The label-extraction branch only activates for description so
the other two environments stay slim.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_environment" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, env_ptr as Integer, env_name as String returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\begin{"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, env_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Note: Generate list items
    proc indent_inc with backend_ptr
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with env_ptr, 24
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with content_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let item_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with content_list, index
            proc emit_indent with backend_ptr
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\item "

            Note: Check for item label (for description lists)
            If proc string_equals from StringCore with env_name, "description":
                Let item_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with item_ptr, 0
                If item_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
                    Let label be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with item_ptr, 8
                    If proc string_length from StringCore with label is greater than 0:
                        proc emit with backend_ptr, "["
                        proc emit with backend_ptr, label
                        proc emit with backend_ptr, "] "
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            proc generate_item with backend_ptr, item_ptr
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "\n"

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc indent_dec with backend_ptr

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\end{"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, env_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Equation environments enter math mode for the duration of the body so the
escape-special-chars logic in generate_literal can branch correctly: math
mode preserves $ ^ _ etc. as syntax rather than escaping them. The math
mode flag is saved/restored around the body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_equation_environment" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, eq_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get environment name if stored, otherwise use "equation"
    Let env_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with eq_ptr, 8

    If proc string_length from StringCore with env_name is equal to 0:
        Set env_name to "equation"
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\begin{"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, env_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Note: Set math mode flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 1

    Note: Generate equation content
    proc indent_inc with backend_ptr
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with eq_ptr, 24
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_indent with backend_ptr
        proc generate_content_list with backend_ptr, content_list
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "\n"
    End If
    proc indent_dec with backend_ptr

    Note: Clear math mode flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 0

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\end{"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, env_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}\n"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Text Formatting Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Text formatting commands (\textbf, \textit, \emph, \underline, \texttt)
share a single emitter that varies only in command name. Body may be a
plain string OR a nested HIR node (e.g., bold containing italic) - we
prefer the string fast path when present, fall back to recursion otherwise.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_text_format" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, format_ptr as Integer, command_name as String returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, command_name
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"

    Note: Get text content
    Let text_content be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with format_ptr, 8
    If proc string_length from StringCore with text_content is greater than 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, text_content
    Otherwise:
        Note: Generate nested content
        Let nested_content be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with format_ptr, 16
        If nested_content is not equal to 0:
            proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, nested_content
        End If
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Math Mode Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inline math is delimited by $...$ and stays on the same line as surrounding
text. Math mode flag is set so escape_latex_text leaves $^_ alone.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_inline" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, math_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "$"

    Note: Set math mode flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 1

    Note: Generate math content
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 8
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_math_content with backend_ptr, content_list
    End If

    Note: Clear math mode flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 0

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "$"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Display math \[...\] is the preferred form over $$...$$ because the former
respects the displaymath environment's amsmath compatibility while the
latter has LaTeX2e quirks. Newlines and indentation are added for human
readability.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_display" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, math_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\[\n"

    Note: Set math mode flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 1

    Note: Generate math content
    proc indent_inc with backend_ptr
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with math_ptr, 8
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_indent with backend_ptr
        proc generate_math_content with backend_ptr, content_list
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "\n"
    End If
    proc indent_dec with backend_ptr

    Note: Clear math mode flag
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24, 0

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\]\n"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iterates over math nodes within a math-mode region; dispatch happens in
generate_math_node which knows the math-specific node taxonomy
(frac, sqrt, sum, integral, etc.) distinct from text-mode nodes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_content" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, content_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with content_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let node_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with content_list, index
        proc generate_math_node with backend_ptr, node_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatch table for math-mode HIR nodes. Operators like sum/int/prod/lim
share generate_math_operator parameterised by the LaTeX command name,
keeping the operator family extensible without growing the dispatcher.
Falls back to generate_hir_node for non-math primitive nodes (identifiers,
literals, calls) that can appear inside math.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_node" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with node_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_FRAC:
        Return proc generate_math_frac with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_SQRT:
        Return proc generate_math_sqrt with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUM:
        Return proc generate_math_operator with backend_ptr, node_ptr, "sum"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_INT:
        Return proc generate_math_operator with backend_ptr, node_ptr, "int"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_PROD:
        Return proc generate_math_operator with backend_ptr, node_ptr, "prod"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_LIMIT:
        Return proc generate_math_operator with backend_ptr, node_ptr, "lim"
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUPERSCRIPT:
        Return proc generate_math_superscript with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to LaTeXHIR.HIR_LATEX_MATH_SUBSCRIPT:
        Return proc generate_math_subscript with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc generate_math_identifier with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_literal with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_math_command with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise:
        Note: Generic math content
        Return proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
\frac{numerator}{denominator} requires two consecutive brace groups; we
emit them in order. If a side is missing we still emit empty braces so the
LaTeX command stays syntactically valid.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_frac" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, frac_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\frac{"

    Note: Generate numerator
    Let numerator_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with frac_ptr, 8
    If numerator_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, numerator_ptr
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}{"

    Note: Generate denominator
    Let denominator_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with frac_ptr, 16
    If denominator_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, denominator_ptr
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
\sqrt has two forms: \sqrt{x} for square root and \sqrt[n]{x} for the nth
root. We branch on whether the root-degree pointer is non-null to choose
the bracketed form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_sqrt" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, sqrt_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check for optional root degree (nth root)
    Let root_degree_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with sqrt_ptr, 16

    If root_degree_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\sqrt["
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, root_degree_ptr
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "]{"
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\sqrt{"
    End If

    Note: Generate radicand
    Let radicand_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with sqrt_ptr, 8
    If radicand_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, radicand_ptr
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Big operators (sum, int, prod, lim) take optional subscript (lower limit)
and superscript (upper limit) followed by an operand. Subscript-before-
superscript order matters because LaTeX renders them differently based on
sequence in display vs. text style.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_operator" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, op_ptr as Integer, op_name as String returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\"
    proc emit with backend_ptr, op_name

    Note: Generate subscript (lower limit) if present
    Let subscript_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with op_ptr, 8
    If subscript_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "_{"
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, subscript_ptr
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"
    End If

    Note: Generate superscript (upper limit) if present
    Let superscript_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with op_ptr, 16
    If superscript_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "^{"
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, superscript_ptr
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"
    End If

    Note: Generate operand if present
    Let operand_ptr be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with op_ptr, 24
    If operand_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, " "
        proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, operand_ptr
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stand-alone superscript node (^{...}) without an attached operator;
generated for HIR expressions like x^2 where x is an identifier rather
than an operator with limits.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_superscript" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, sup_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "^{"

    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with sup_ptr, 8
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_math_content with backend_ptr, content_list
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stand-alone subscript node (_{...}); mirrors generate_math_superscript. We
always brace-wrap the content even when it's a single character because
multi-character subscripts without braces silently truncate in LaTeX.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_subscript" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, sub_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "_{"

    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with sub_ptr, 8
    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_math_content with backend_ptr, content_list
    End If

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Math identifiers (variable names) are emitted verbatim because LaTeX
already italicises identifiers in math mode automatically; we do not wrap
them in \mathit{} which would be redundant and forbid kerning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_identifier" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, id_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with id_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, name
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generic math-mode function call emission for HIR_CALL nodes that did not
match a specialised math node kind. Arguments are emitted as brace groups
per LaTeX convention - never as comma-separated parentheses like a
programming-language call.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_math_command" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, call_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generic math command
    Let command_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with call_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, command_name

    Note: Generate arguments
    Let args_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with call_ptr, 16
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with args_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let arg_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, index
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"
            proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, arg_ptr
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Citation and Reference Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
\cite{key} or \cite[note]{key} - the optional note (e.g., page number)
appears in brackets when present. The note is typeset together with the
citation by BibTeX, e.g., \cite[p. 5]{smith2020}.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_citation" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, cite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check for optional note
    Let note_text be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with cite_ptr, 16

    If proc string_length from StringCore with note_text is greater than 0:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\cite["
        proc emit with backend_ptr, note_text
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "]{"
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\cite{"
    End If

    Let cite_key be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with cite_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, cite_key

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cross-reference \ref{label} resolves to the auto-numbered counter at the
label site (section number, equation number, etc.). Distinct from citation
which goes through BibTeX.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_reference" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, ref_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\ref{"

    Let ref_label be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with ref_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, ref_label

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
\label{name} attaches an identifier to the most recent counter; later
\ref{name} resolves to that counter. The label name is emitted verbatim
because LaTeX label names allow no special characters.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_label" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, label_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc emit with backend_ptr, "\\label{"

    Let label_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with label_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, label_name

    proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Generic HIR Node Generation
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Fallback dispatcher for generic HIR nodes that may appear inside any
LaTeX context. node_type > 5000 is the LaTeX-extended kind range, so we
route those back through generate_item; otherwise we handle primitive
node kinds (literal, identifier, block, call) directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_hir_node" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with node_ptr, 0

    Note: Try LaTeX-specific generation first
    If node_type is greater than 5000:
        Return proc generate_item with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    End If

    Note: Generic HIR nodes
    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_literal with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with node_ptr, 8
        proc emit with backend_ptr, name
        Return 1
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_block with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    Otherwise If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_call with backend_ptr, node_ptr
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Literal emission must escape LaTeX special characters in text mode but
preserve them verbatim in math mode where they have syntactic meaning
(^,_,$). The in_math flag at offset 24 selects between the two paths.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
Untrusted literal text could embed LaTeX command sequences if not escaped;
escape_latex_text neutralises \,{,},$,%,&,#,_,^,~ which are the only
characters LaTeX treats as command/group syntax.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "generate_literal" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, literal_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let value be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with literal_ptr, 8

    Note: Escape special LaTeX characters if not in math mode
    Let in_math be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 24
    If in_math is equal to 0:
        Let escaped be proc escape_latex_text with value
        proc emit with backend_ptr, escaped
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, value
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR_BLOCK nodes can carry their content list at offset 8 (statement-style)
or offset 16 (sub-block style); we probe offset 8 first then fall back to
offset 16 to handle both encodings. Reads are pointer-safe because each
offset is checked before deref.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, block_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let content_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with block_ptr, 8

    If content_list is not equal to 0:
        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let node_type be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with block_ptr, 0
            If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
                Let content_list_from_offset be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with block_ptr, 16
                If content_list_from_offset is not equal to 0:
                    Set content_list to content_list_from_offset
                End If
            End If
        End If

        proc generate_content_list with backend_ptr, content_list
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Generic HIR_CALL emission as a LaTeX command: function name followed by
brace-grouped arguments rather than parenthesised comma-separated args.
Used as the default for text-mode calls and for math-mode commands that
didn't match a specialised generator.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, call_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let function_name be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with call_ptr, 8
    proc emit with backend_ptr, function_name

    Let args_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with call_ptr, 16
    If args_list is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with args_list
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than count:
            Let arg_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with args_list, index
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "{"
            proc generate_hir_node with backend_ptr, arg_ptr
            proc emit with backend_ptr, "}"
            Set index to index plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iterates child nodes within an environment/section body. Distinct from
generate_item_list which is reserved for the top-level document body so
the contracts (no surrounding context vs. inside-environment context) stay
explicit at call sites.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_content_list" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, content_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with content_list
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let node_ptr be proc list_get from ListCore with content_list, index
        proc generate_item with backend_ptr, node_ptr
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: LaTeX Text Escaping
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
LaTeX reserves ten characters: backslash, braces, dollar, percent, ampersand,
hash, underscore, caret, tilde. Each requires a different escape because some
need a trailing {} (^, ~) to consume the next character, others need a literal
backslash prefix, and backslash itself needs the textbackslash command since
\\ means line break.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
This is the canonical sanitiser for user-controlled strings entering text
mode. A literal that bypasses this routine could inject arbitrary LaTeX
commands, including \write18 (shell escape) if the document is compiled
with -shell-escape. All generate_literal text-mode paths must funnel here.
@End Security_Scope
@Performance_Hints:
Per-character string concatenation is O(n^2) for n input characters; for
very large literal blocks (e.g. embedded data tables) the caller should
batch-emit via a dedicated builder rather than this routine.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "escape_latex_text" that takes text as String returns String:
    Let result be ""
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with text
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than length:
        Note: string_char_at returns the character's integer code directly.
        Let char_code be proc string_char_at from StringCore with text, index

        Note: Escape special LaTeX characters
        If char_code is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\textbackslash{}"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 123:  Note: {
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\{"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 125:  Note: }
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\}"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 36:  Note: $
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\$"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 37:  Note: %
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\%"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 38:  Note: &
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\&"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 35:  Note: #
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\#"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 95:  Note: _
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\_"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 94:  Note: ^
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\^{}"
        Otherwise If char_code is equal to 126:  Note: ~
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\\~{}"
        Otherwise:
            Let char_str be proc char_to_string from StringCore with char_code
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, char_str
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Output Management
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single append point for the LaTeX output buffer; centralising the
read-string/concat/write-string sequence means future buffered-output
upgrades replace only this routine. All other generators flow through here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    Let current be proc memory_get_pointer from Memory with backend_ptr, 0
    Let new_output be proc string_concat from StringPrim with current, text
    proc memory_set_pointer from Memory with backend_ptr, 0, new_output
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two-space indentation per level for generated LaTeX source readability.
LaTeX ignores horizontal whitespace in text mode (collapsed runs), but
human readers and editors rely on indentation to read environment nesting.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_indent" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let level be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 8
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than level:
        proc emit with backend_ptr, "  "
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Increments before emitting the body of an environment so the body itself
sits one level deeper than the \begin line. Paired with indent_dec around
the body to maintain depth invariants.
@End Reasoning
Process called "indent_inc" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let level be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 8
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 8, level plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Guards against unbalanced calls by clamping at zero rather than going
negative; a buggy caller that double-decrements still produces valid
(if mis-indented) output rather than an out-of-range counter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "indent_dec" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let level be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 8
    If level is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 8, level minus 1
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning:
Errors are accumulated rather than aborting so the entire document can be
walked and all problems reported in one pass; the caller checks has_errors
after translate() and inspects get_errors for the full list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_error" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Let errors_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 16
    proc list_append from ListCore with errors_list, message
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the internal list pointer rather than copying; the caller must not
destroy the list because the backend retains ownership until destroy.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_errors" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean shortcut so callers can branch on success without retrieving the
full error list; returns 1 for any-errors and 0 for none.
@End Reasoning
Process called "has_errors" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let errors_list be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with backend_ptr, 16
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with errors_list

    If count is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process
